---
import Container from "@components/Container.astro";
import PageLayout from "@layouts/PageLayout.astro";
import Link from "@components/Link.astro";

const title = "About | Creatives for Collective Action";
const description =
  "Learn about Creatives for Collective Action, a Boston-based creative action collective connecting artists, organizers, and communities through justice-centered public art.";
---

<PageLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <Container>
    <div class="space-y-20">
      <section class="animate space-y-6">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest opacity-75">
          About
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-black dark:text-white sm:text-5xl">
            About Creatives for Collective Action
          </h1>

          <p class="text-xl font-semibold leading-snug text-black dark:text-white">
            Creatives for Collective Action is a Boston-based collective connecting artists, organizers,
            justice organizations, cultural spaces, and community members through justice-centered public art.
          </p>

          <p>
            We believe art is not only a tool for communication. It is a way to build relationships, make
            movements visible, invite participation, and help communities imagine what justice can look and feel like.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="animate space-y-4">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
          Our Mission
        </h2>

        <p>
          We are a Boston-based creative action collective connecting artists, organizers, and communities in
          order to bolster existing immigration, climate, and other community-based justice work. We build
          relationships, host gatherings and workshops, support justice-based art projects, and help local
          organizations collaborate with artists in ethical, community-centered ways, along with providing
          resources for public-facing creative works.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="animate space-y-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
          Our Theory of Change
        </h2>

        <article class="space-y-2">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">Problem</h3>
          <p>
            Boston has a thriving community of artists, justice organizations, cultural spaces, and community
            campaigns, but they are often disconnected or siloed. Justice organizations need compelling creative
            tools to move people, artists need pathways into meaningful and fairly compensated justice work, and
            communities need art practices that help them gather, grieve, imagine, celebrate, and act.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="space-y-2">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">Intervention</h3>
          <p>
            We build a Boston-based network that connects artists, organizers, and communities through open
            calls, gatherings, art builds, creative action support, workshops, and paid commissions.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="space-y-2">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">Mechanism</h3>
          <p>
            When artists and justice organizations build trust before crisis moments, they can collaborate
            faster, more ethically, and more beautifully. Art makes campaigns more visible, emotionally resonant,
            participatory, and accessible. Recurring gatherings and shared tools prevent isolation and create a
            community of art and justice.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="space-y-2">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">Outcomes</h3>
          <p>
            Artists gain community, mentorship, visibility, and paid opportunities. Justice organizations gain
            creative capacity. Communities experience public art and cultural events that invite participation
            and deepen civic imagination. Boston’s movement ecosystem becomes more connected, expressive,
            joyful, and effective.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="space-y-2">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">Long-Term Dream</h3>
          <p>
            Boston becomes a city where justice work is culturally alive: campaigns have artists, artists have
            movements, communities have creative public rituals, and art becomes a practical tool for collective action.
          </p>
        </article>
      </section>

      <section class="animate space-y-4">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
          What We Are Building
        </h2>

        <p>
          Creatives for Collective Action is in its early stages. We are building:
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-6">
          <li>A collective space for artists, organizers, activists, cultural workers, and community members</li>
          <li>A growing network of creatives interested in justice-based work</li>
          <li>Relationships with Boston-area justice organizations and community groups</li>
          <li>Gatherings, workshops, and art builds</li>
          <li>
            Public-facing creative projects, including banners, signs, zines, installations, social graphics,
            visual storytelling, and other forms of art for collective action
          </li>
          <li>Pathways for paid commissions and creative collaboration</li>
          <li>
            In-person and online opportunities for artists to sell, share, or contribute work in support of
            community and justice causes
          </li>
          <li>
            Shared material resources and, eventually, a studio space for artists and activists to work together
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="animate space-y-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
          Founding Team
        </h2>

        <p>
          Creatives for Collective Action is being built by Ari, Adam, and Sohara, three Boston-based artists
          and organizers who believe in the power of art to support justice work, strengthen community, and
          create public imagination.
        </p>

        <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-3">
          <article class="space-y-2 rounded-2xl border border-black/10 p-5 dark:border-white/10">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">Ari</h3>
            <p>Bio coming soon.</p>
          </article>

          <article class="space-y-2 rounded-2xl border border-black/10 p-5 dark:border-white/10">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">Adam</h3>
            <p>Bio coming soon.</p>
          </article>

          <article class="space-y-2 rounded-2xl border border-black/10 p-5 dark:border-white/10">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">Sohara</h3>
            <p>Bio coming soon.</p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="animate space-y-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
          Our Values
        </h2>

        <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
          <article class="space-y-2">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">Community Accountability</h3>
            <p>
              We believe creative work should be rooted in the needs, leadership, and consent of the communities
              most affected by the issues being addressed.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="space-y-2">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">Collaboration Over Extraction</h3>
            <p>
              We want to build relationships that are mutual, respectful, and sustainable. Artists should not be
              treated as free labor, and communities should not be treated as backdrops for art.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="space-y-2">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">Fair Compensation</h3>
            <p>
              We are committed to building pathways for artists to access meaningful and fairly compensated
              justice-based opportunities whenever resources are available.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="space-y-2">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">Accessibility</h3>
            <p>
              We want our gatherings, projects, and creative practices to be welcoming to people with different
              levels of experience, ability, income, language, and access needs.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="space-y-2">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">Low-Barrier Participation</h3>
            <p>
              You do not need to be a professional artist to be part of this work. We welcome professional
              artists, emerging artists, hobbyists, organizers, students, cultural workers, and community members.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="space-y-2">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">Public Imagination</h3>
            <p>
              We believe art can help communities imagine beyond the world as it is and create shared visions
              for the world we are trying to build.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="space-y-2 md:col-span-2">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">Care, Joy, and Collective Action</h3>
            <p>
              Justice work can hold grief, urgency, anger, celebration, beauty, and joy. We believe creative
              practice can help communities gather, grieve, imagine, celebrate, and act.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="animate space-y-4 rounded-2xl border border-black/10 p-6 dark:border-white/10">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
          Get Involved
        </h2>

        <p>
          We are currently gathering artists, organizers, cultural workers, justice organizations, and community
          members who want to help shape this collective.
        </p>

        <p>
          Whether you are a professional artist, an emerging creative, an organizer, a cultural space, a community
          member, or someone who is simply curious, there is a place for you in this work.
        </p>

        <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
          <Link href="/contact">
            Join the Open Call
          </Link>
          <Link href="/contact">
            Collaborate With Us
          </Link>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>
  </Container>
</PageLayout>
